to</div><div class="_1RdHf"><div class="SwyeB"><div data-testid="ai__text-editor" class="_5jyLv" style="position: relative;"><div class="_3Ir8J" style="padding-right: 32px;"><div data-slate-editor="true" data-key="399" contenteditable="true" class="src-pages-AiSetupPage-___AiSetupPage-module__editorContainer___32pvo" autocorrect="on" spellcheck="true" role="textbox" data-gramm="false" style="outline: none; white-space: pre-wrap; overflow-wrap: break-word; -webkit-user-modify: read-write-plaintext-only;"><div class="_28quz" data-key="400"><div data-testid="ai__text-editor__text-node" class="FJTwP _2Q_Ub"><span data-key="401"><span data-slate-leaf="true" data-offset-key="401:0"><span data-slate-content="true">llama</span></span></span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="src-pages-AiSetupPage-___AiSetupPage-module__repliesContainer___1oScj"><div data-testid="ai__replies-label" class="_3IY_S _332L7 src-pages-AiSetupPage-___AiSetupPage-module__label___19jmA"><span>bot replies </span>with</div><div class="src-pages-AiSetupPage-___AiSetupPage-module__repliesList___1u0on"><div><div class="src-pages-AiSetupPage-___AiSetupPage-module__actionContainer___1I9JJ"><div class="_1RdHf _2Gt6d"><div class="SwyeB"><div class="_3Ir8J" style="padding-right: 0px;"><textarea data-testid="ai__reply-text-input" rows="1" class="src-pages-AiSetupPage-___AiSetupPage-module__actionItemInputLayout___vxHdo test-intent-reply-text-input src-pages-AiSetupPage-___AiSetupPage-module__textActionTextarea___1AliJ" placeholder="Enter reply text..." type="text" style="height: 112px;">The llama (/lm/, Spanish pronunciation: [ama]) (Lama glama) is a domesticated South American camelid, widely used as a meat and pack animal by Andean cultures since the Pre-Columbian era.

Llamas are very social animals and live with others as a herd. Their wool is very soft and lanolin-free. Llamas can learn simple tasks after a few repetitions. When using a pack, they can carry about 25 to 30% of their body weight for 8 to 13 km (58 miles). The name llama (in the past also spelled "lama" or "glama") was adopted by European settlers from native Peruvians.

Llamas appear to have originated from the central plains of North America about 40 million years ago. They migrated to South America about three million years ago during the Great American Interchange. By the end of the last ice age (10,00012,000 years ago), camelids were extinct in North America. As of 2007, there were over seven million llamas and alpacas in South America, and due to importation from South America in the late 20th century, there are now over 158,000 llamas and 100,000 alpacas in the United States and Canada.</textarea><div class="_2qLvL _25Jqu" style="height: 20px;"></div></div></div></div><div class="src-pages-AiSetupPage-___AiSetupPage-module__removeActionButtonContainer___3A5DT"></div></div><div class="src-pages-AiSetupPage-___AiSetupPage-module__divider___JCv2l"></div></div><div><div class="src-pages-AiSetupPage-___AiSetupPage-module__infoText___d3Byq"><svg width="13" height="13" viewBox="0 0 13 13" class="src-pages-AiSetupPage-___AiSetupPage-module__iconGray___3FNXn src-pages-AiSetupPage-___AiSetupPage-module__iconInText___8OLlr src-pages-AiSetupPage-___AiSetupPage-module__addIcon___1Nq21"><path fill="currentColor" fill-rule="evenodd" d="M6 6V.5a.5.5 0 1 1 1 0V6h5.5a.5.5 0 1 1 0 1H7v5.5a.5.5 0 1 1-1 0V7H.5a.5.5 0 1 1 0-1H6z"></path></svg> add <button class="test-add-reply-block _39g46" data-testid="ai__reply-block-add-button">Block</button> or <button class="test-add-reply-text _39g46" data-testid="ai__reply-text-add-button">Text</button> reply</div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="src-pages-AiSetupPage-___AiSetupPage-module__lineLayout___2kOW_ src-pages-AiSetupPage-___AiSetupPage-module__listBottom___1mFfP"></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="_3hlfA"><div><div></div></div></div></div>
